  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka remittances down 42-pct in June 2022 in non-credible peg",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s official remittances were down 42 percent from a year earlier 274.1 million US dollars, with money being channeled to traditional gross settlement systems, with the credibility of a pegged exchange rate being lost.",
        "Sri Lanka usually gets around 500 to 600 million US dollars a month through official channels.",
        "Around May 2021 the central bank started to enforce a non-credible peg at 199.50 to the US dollar and by August 2021 parallel exchange rates started to develop in the official market.",
        "Sri Lanka rupee 203 non-credible peg to US dollar hanging by a thread",
        "Sri Lanka rupee non-credible peg breaks to 211-215 to US dollar",
        "Remittances started drop sharply from September as banks were prohibited from offering higher rates to exporters.",
        "In early May the rupee was trading around 370/380 to the US dollar and Middle East exchange houses were offering around 102 rupees to the Dirham.",
        "A new non-credible peg was then imposed at 360 to the US dollar. (Colombo/July11/2022)"
      ],
